rticle PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2152-2669</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>May</Month><Day>20</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Clinical lymphoma, myeloma &amp; leukemia</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Clin Lymphoma Myeloma Leuk</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Pretransplant Blinatumomab Is Associated With Reduced Relapse and Improved Disease-Free Survival in Adults With B-Cell ALL Undergoing Allogeneic Hematopoietic Cell Transplantation.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S2152-2650(26)00148-5</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.clml.2026.05.005</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Adults with B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (B-ALL) have inferior survival compared with pediatric patients, and pretransplant measurable residual disease (MRD) predicts relapse after allogeneic hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (HSCT). Blinatumomab, a bispecific CD3/CD19 antibody, may eradicate MRD, but its pretransplant impact is unclear.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVES" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To evaluate the effect of pretransplant blinatumomab on survival, relapse, graft-versus-host disease (GVHD), and GVHD-free, relapse-free survival (GRFS) in this single-center retrospective cohort adult B-ALL patients.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="PATIENTS AND METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">This single-center retrospective study included 145 predominantly Hispanic adults (&#x2265;18 years) with B-ALL who underwent HSCT between 2013 and 2025, with 56 receiving pretransplant blinatumomab and 89 controls. Outcomes were overall survival (OS), disease-free survival (DFS), cumulative incidence of relapse (CIR), non-relapse mortality (NRM), GRFS, and grade III/IV acute and severe chronic GVHD.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Among 145 adults (median age 42 years), 76.6% were Hispanic and 38.6% received pretransplant blinatumomab. The 2-year OS and DFS for the cohort were 88.6% and 70.3%, respectively. Blinatumomab was associated with improved 2-year DFS (84.4% vs. 62.8%; HR 0.45; 95% CI, 0.21-0.97; P = .042) and reduced CIR (7.4% vs. 31.0%; HR 0.27; 95% CI, 0.09-0.77; P = .014) on univariate analysis. These benefits persisted on multivariate analysis adjusting for disease stage, cytogenetics, and MRD status (DFS: HR = 0.34; 95% CI, 0.15-0.80; P = .014; CIR: HR = 0.26; 95% CI, 0.09-0.74; P = .012). NRM, GRFS, and grade III/IV acute and severe chronic GVHD did not differ.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">In this predominantly Hispanic adult B-ALL population, pretransplant blinatumomab safely reduces relapse risk and improves disease-free survival without increasing post-transplant toxicity.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ginosyan</LastName><ForeName>Anush A</ForeName><Initials>AA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine, Keck School of Medicine, University of Southern California, Los Angeles, CA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ashouri</LastName><ForeName>Karam</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine, Keck School of Medicine, University of Southern California, Los Angeles, CA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Chen</LastName><ForeName>Tiffany</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Jane Anne Nohl Division of Hematology and Center for the Study of Blood Disease, Division of Hematology, University of Southern California, Norris Comprehensive Cancer Center, Los Angeles, CA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Grove</LastName><ForeName>Sophie</ForeName><I